I think basically every standing lighter barbell lift like bicep curls, reverse curls, high pulls, upright rows, etc. should be done the same way as the Press 2.0, keeping knees locked and using hip drive and momentum to get through the sticking points in a smooth movement...

If you don't lock your knees everything turns into a meme clean and jerk variation and if you keep too strict you're doing nothing and can never actually progress and lift heavy enough to grow. Hip drive and pushing with glutes etc. but fully locked knees is the perfect balance.

IIRC in Wolfe's Nessus in BOTNS the Southern part of the town is also in ruins. I think these are all references to Gehenna which is the image of Hell itself being South of Jerusalem in the Bible.

In The Shadow over Innsmouth H. P. Lovecraft describes the Southern part of the town as "omnipresent desolation", collapsing roofs, "utter desertion", rotting wharves, etc. Gene Wolfe in "Slow Children at Play" says to the South all was ruins and derelict buildings.
